Sir John Floyer's "Medicina gerocomica" in the 17th century already notes that old men have lower body temperature and slower heartbeats than younger men, hinting at metabolism's role in preserving health and aging. 17th century or the Cindy Century as I like to call it.

"The Humours are more phlegmatic and melancholic and the Blood colder than in their Youth, the crude watery Serum abounds that makes them more subject to chronic Disease; the Pulse is obscure and slower than in Youth, Obesity" - JF

Literally describing decaying thyroid function!

In the 17th century doctors already understood the principles behind medicine better than most do today. They didn't have thyroid medication so a lot of the cures were just keeping body temperature up using warm baths and warm clothing, but they KNEW what aging actually meant.
